---
description: FastAPI backend rules
globs: backend/**, api/**, server/**, app/**.py
---

Backend stack:
- Python 3.x
- FastAPI
- Pydantic
- Supabase (PostgreSQL) for persistence
- Redis for cache, rate limiting, session state, and queues
- OpenAI API for text generation, embeddings, speech-to-text, text-to-speech
- Twilio for WhatsApp and SMS
- Configurable email provider (e.g. SendGrid, AWS SES) for ticket ingestion and notifications
- WebSockets for real-time chat and streaming
- Event streaming (e.g. Kafka or AWS SQS/SNS) for async workflows where required

Backend rules:
- Use clean architecture.
- Routes/controllers should only handle HTTP/WebSocket concerns.
- Business logic must live in services (ticketing, RAG, agents, channels, NLP).
- Database access must live in repositories.
- Validation must be done using Pydantic schemas/models.
- Use dependency injection patterns where appropriate.
- Use async I/O for external calls (OpenAI, Twilio, email, Supabase).
- Use pagination for list endpoints.
- Use consistent response models.
- Use centralized exception handling.

API conventions:
- Follow RESTful naming; version APIs (e.g. /api/v1/).
- Use proper status codes; return predictable response structure.
- Do not leak internal stack traces or raw database errors.
- Support WebSocket endpoints for chat and real-time features per API_SPEC.md.

Preferred backend structure:
- backend/api/routes/          (HTTP + WebSocket routes)
- backend/api/dependencies/
- backend/services/            (business logic: ticketing, rag, agents, channels, nlp)
- backend/repositories/
- backend/models/
- backend/schemas/
- backend/core/                (config, security, logging)
- backend/integrations/       (Twilio, email, Slack/Teams, CRM adapters)
- backend/utils/
- backend/tests/

Coding expectations:
- Add type hints to functions.
- Add docstrings for non-trivial service methods.
- Keep routes thin and declarative.
- Keep service methods focused and testable.
- Reuse existing utilities before creating new ones.
- Isolate channel adapters (Twilio, email, etc.) behind a unified conversation/channel interface.

Do not:
- Put SQL or ORM-heavy logic inside route files.
- Put business logic inside Pydantic schemas.
- Put environment variables directly across many files; centralize config.
- Mix unrelated domains in the same service file.
- Hardcode Twilio credentials, OpenAI keys, or email provider secrets; use config/env.